cause the self-discipline it imposes converts the properly human quality of action without a predetermined goal into a lack, a fault, or a state of guilt: a debt that cannot be settled. Stimilli argues that this lack, which is impossible to fill, should be seen as the basis of the economy of hedonism and consumption that has governed global economies in recent years and as the premise of the current economy of debt.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAsceticism. 0aCapitalismxReligious aspects. 0aCapitalism. 0aReligion and sociology. 4aBusiness and Economics : Economy and Society. 4aPhilosophy : Continental Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Economy. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Theology. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aBove, Arianna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEsposito, Roberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846416940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438464169423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438464169/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles